{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496349"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:44:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1342"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1342"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.13,0.08,0.56,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50626"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1342"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1342"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35859"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"176"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8287"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13949"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36959"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44267"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50626"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old man is referred to a haematology clinic following a finding of elevated globulins on his liver function test. He has not noticed any bony pain, fatigue, infections, or easy bruising/bleeding. Physical examination is unremarkable, with no evidence of lymphadenopathy, organomegaly, or spinal tenderness on palpation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests are summarised as below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 140 g/L (135-180)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 10 g/L (4-11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets: 285 g/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 70 umol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EeGFR: 90 ml/min (\u226590)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECorrected calcium: 2.45 mmol/L (2.1-2.6)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlobulin: 44 g/L (25-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImmunoglobulin (Ig) G: 18 g/L (6.5-16)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIgA: 0.8 g/L (0.6-4.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIgM: 0.4 g/L (0.5-3.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eserum protein electrophoresis: monoclonal IgG Kappa protein detected, 4 g/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efree kappa light chain: 56 mg/L (3.3 to 19.4)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efree lambda light chain: 18 mg/L (5.7 to 26.3)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ekappa to lambda ratio: 3.1 (0.26 to 1.65)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this picture?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple Myeloma","Smoldering Multiple Myeloma","Immunoglobulin G4-related disease","Monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance","Myelodysplastic Neoplasm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient was found to have elevated globulins which led to identification of an IgG Kappa monoclonal protein (also known as paraprotein) without any symptoms or other laboratory abnormalities. The most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003EMonoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance (MGUS)\u003C/strong\u003E. MGUS, smoldering (asymptomatic) multiple myeloma, and multiple myeloma are monoclonal plasma cell dyscrasias which can be distinguished by several clinical, imaging, and laboratory features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMGUS is an asymptomatic precursor condition defined by the presence of a low level of serum monoclonal protein and bone marrow plasma cells (\u0026lt;30 g/L and 10%, respectively) without myeloma-defining events\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E These are a group of clinical, imaging, and laboratory features known as the \u0022SLiM CRAB\u0022 criteria:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESixty percent of plasma cells in the bone marrow\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELight chain ratio between the involved and uninvolved of \u0026gt;100\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMRI showing \u0026gt;1 focal lesion of \u22655 mm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium elevated\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERenal dysfunction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAnaemia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBone lesions on imaging\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMGUS has a low risk of progression to multiple myeloma - around 1% per year depending on various prognostic factors, however patients should be monitored regularly. It is important to note that monoclonal proteins may also be associated with lymphoproliferative disorders (e.g., Waldenstr\u00f6m macroglobulinemia).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003ESmoldering Multiple Myeloma, \u003C/strong\u003Ethere is a higher level of serum monoclonal protein (\u226530 g/L) and bone marrow plasma cells (10-59%) than MGUS. However patients remain asymptomatic without myeloma-defining events described above. There is also a risk of progression to multiple myeloma, hence patients require regular monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple Myeloma\u003C/strong\u003E is a plasma cell neoplasm with associated end-organ damage in many cases (\u0022CRAB\u0022 criteria described above). However, some patients may meet the diagnostic criteria due to a very high bone marrow plasma cell burden, serum free light chain level, or more than 1 focal lesion of \u2265 5 mm on MRI (\u0022SLiM\u0022 criteria described above). Common clinical presentations are bone pain, renal failure, or pathological fracture. As the patient presents with an elevated paraprotein without these features, multiple myeloma is unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyelodysplastic neoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E, or myelodysplastic syndrome (MDS), is a group of malignant haematopoietic stem cell disorders which is most common in the elderly. It often manifests with cytopenia, macrocytosis, with dysplastic features seen on blood film or bone marrow evaluation. It may progress to Acute myeloid leukaemia. A monoclonal protein is not seen in MDS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients with\u003Cstrong\u003E Immunoglobulin G4-related disease\u003C/strong\u003E present with elevated serum IgG4 levels and often have organ involvement such as pancreatitis, sclerosing cholangitis, or retroperitoneal fibrosis. However, the hypergammaglobulinemia seen in this case is polyclonal, rather than monoclonal protein seen in MGUS, Smoldering multiple myeloma, and Multiple myeloma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance (MGUS) is an asymptomatic precursor condition.","In MGUS, there is a low level of serum monoclonal protein and bone marrow plasma cell without myeloma-defining events.","MGUS carries a risk of 1-2% chance of progressing to multiple myeloma each year, depending on various prognostic factors."],"references":["Allen K. Hereditary haemochromatosis: Diagnosis and management. Australian family physician. 2010 Dec;39(12):938-41.","Eslick R, Talaulikar D. Multiple myeloma: from diagnosis to treatment. Australian family physician. 2013 Oct;42(10):684-8.","Cowan AJ, Green DJ, Kwok M, et al. Diagnosis and Management of Multiple Myeloma: A Review. JAMA. 2022;327(5):464\u2013477. doi:10.1001/jama.2022.0003"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35859"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1342"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35859"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-14T13:05:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-15T15:24:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1342"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50626"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"